    "slug": "html-document-structure",
    "title": "HTML Document Structure",
    "description": "HTML document structure is the required skeleton every valid page must follow to render correctly.",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "level": 1,
        "text": "The Anatomy of an HTML Document"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          {
            "value": "Every HTML page follows a fixed structure. It starts with a "
          },
          {
            "value": "DOCTYPE declaration",
            "bold": true
          },
          {
            "value": ", followed by the "
          },
          {
            "value": "html",
            "highlight": true
          },
          {
            "value": " root element containing two children: "
          },
          {
            "value": "head",
            "highlight": true
          },
          {
            "value": " and "
          },
          {
            "value": "body",
            "highlight": true
          },
          {
            "value": ". The head holds metadata the browser needs. The body holds everything users see and interact with. The full specification is maintained by the "
          },
          {
            "value": "WHATWG HTML Standard",
            "link": "https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/syntax.html"
          },
          {
            "value": "."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "level": 2,
        "text": "Document Structure at a Glance"
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "headers": [
          "Part",
          "Element",
          "Purpose",
          "Visible to User"
        ],
        "rows": [
          [
            "Document type",
            "<!DOCTYPE html>",
            "Tells browser to use modern HTML5 standards mode",
            "No"
          ],
          [
            "Root",
            "<html lang='en'>",
            "Wraps the entire document, declares language",
            "No"
          ],
          [
            "Metadata",
            "<head>",
            "Title, charset, viewport, CSS links, meta tags",
            "No"
          ],
          [
            "Content",
            "<body>",
            "All visible page content and interactive elements",
            "Yes"
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "callout",
        "variant": "info",
        "title": "Why Structure Matters",
        "text": "A missing or incorrect document structure causes browsers to enter quirks mode, producing unpredictable layout bugs that are hard to diagnose and inconsistent across browsers."
      }
    ],
    "examples": [
      {
        "title": "Complete HTML Document Boilerplate",
        "description": "This example shows the production-ready HTML boilerplate used as the starting point for every new web page. Every line has a specific purpose. Understanding what each part does and why it is included prevents a whole category of subtle bugs that only appear in specific browsers or devices.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <!-- Character encoding: must be the very first meta tag in head -->\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n\n  <!-- Viewport: controls layout on mobile devices -->\n  <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n\n  <!-- Page title: shown in browser tab, search results, and bookmarks -->\n  <title>Page Title | Site Name</title>\n\n  <!-- SEO description: 150-160 chars shown in search snippets -->\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"A clear, concise description of this page for search engines.\">\n\n  <!-- Canonical URL: prevents duplicate content issues -->\n  <link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https://example.com/page\">\n\n  <!-- Open Graph: controls how page looks when shared on social media -->\n  <meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Page Title\">\n  <meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Description for social sharing previews.\">\n  <meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\">\n  <meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"https://example.com/og-image.jpg\">\n\n  <!-- External CSS -->\n  <link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"styles.css\">\n\n  <!-- Favicon -->\n  <link rel=\"icon\" type=\"image/svg+xml\" href=\"/favicon.svg\">\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <!-- Skip link: accessibility for keyboard users -->\n  <a href=\"#main-content\" style=\"position:absolute;top:-100%;\">Skip to main content</a>\n\n  <header>\n    <nav aria-label=\"Main navigation\">\n      <!-- navigation links -->\n    </nav>\n  </header>\n\n  <main id=\"main-content\">\n    <h1>Page Heading</h1>\n    <!-- primary page content -->\n  </main>\n\n  <footer>\n    <!-- footer content -->\n  </footer>\n\n  <!-- JS with defer: downloads in parallel, runs after HTML is parsed -->\n  <script src=\"app.js\" defer></script>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
        "output": "Browser renders a blank page with 'Page Heading' as the h1. The tab shows 'Page Title | Site Name'. DevTools shows the full head metadata: charset, viewport, linked resources, and Open Graph tags in the Elements panel.",
        "images": null,
        "video_url": null
      },
      {
        "title": "Head vs Body: What Goes Where",
        "description": "This example shows a side-by-side comparison of what belongs in head and what belongs in body. A common beginner mistake is placing visible content in head or putting meta tags in body. Both cause silent failures with no obvious browser error.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>Head vs Body Demo</title>\n\n  <!-- CORRECT items in head: all invisible to the user -->\n  <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Demonstrates what belongs in head vs body.\">\n  <link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"styles.css\">\n  <link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https://example.com/page\">\n\n  <!-- WRONG: visible content placed in head is ignored by browsers -->\n  <!-- <p>This paragraph will NOT render</p> -->\n  <!-- <h1>This heading will NOT render</h1> -->\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <!-- CORRECT items in body: all visible content -->\n  <h1>Main Heading</h1>\n  <p>Body paragraph text that users read.</p>\n  <img src=\"/photo.jpg\" alt=\"Descriptive alt text\">\n  <a href=\"/about\">About page link</a>\n\n  <!-- WRONG: meta tags placed in body are ignored -->\n  <!-- <meta name=\"description\" content=\"This does nothing in body\"> -->\n\n  <!--\n    Script placement:\n    Option A (recommended): in head with defer attribute, non-blocking\n    Option B (traditional): at the very end of body\n    Never place scripts in the middle of body content.\n  -->\n  <script src=\"app.js\" defer></script>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
        "output": "Page renders only the body content: h1 heading, paragraph, image, and link. All head elements are invisible to the user but visible in DevTools. The commented-out wrong examples confirm that visible content in head and meta tags in body are both silently ignored by browsers.",
        "images": null,
        "video_url": null
      }
    ],
